13)ls -o:
description:
like -l, but do not list group information
output:
raakin@ubuntu-25:~$ ls -o
total 44
drwxr-xr-x 2 raakin 4096 Aug 17 14:51 Desktop
drwxr-xr-x 2 raakin 4096 Aug 17 14:51 Documents
drwxr-xr-x 2 raakin 4096 Aug 19 10:56 Downloads
drwxrwxr-x 2 raakin 4096 Aug 28 09:00 linx
drwxr-xr-x 2 raakin 4096 Aug 17 14:51 Music
drwxrwxr-x 2 raakin 4096 Aug 24 06:19 newc
drwxr-xr-x 2 raakin 4096 Aug 18 10:27 Pictures
drwxr-xr-x 2 raakin 4096 Aug 17 14:51 Public
drwx------ 8 raakin 4096 Aug 18 10:33 snap
drwxr-xr-x 2 raakin 4096 Aug 17 14:51 Templates
drwxr-xr-x 2 raakin 4096 Aug 17 14:51 Videos
remark:
The command ls -o in Linux displays a detailed list of files while omitting the group ownership information from the output.

-------------------------------------------------------------------------
14) ls -p:
descriprion:
 -p, --indicator-style=slash
              append / indicator to directories
output:
raakin@ubuntu-25:~$ ls -p
Desktop/    Downloads/  Music/  Pictures/  snap/       Videos/
Documents/  linx/       newc/   Public/    Templates/
remark:
The command ls -p in Linux lists files and directories, appending a forward slash / to directory names to distinguish them from files.

-------------------------------------------------------------------------
15)ls -q:
description:
 -q, --hide-control-chars
              print ? instead of nongraphic characters
output:
raakin@ubuntu-25:~$ ls -q
Desktop    Downloads  Music  Pictures  snap       Videos
Documents  linx       newc   Public    Templates
remarks:
The command ls -q in Linux displays the contents of a directory, replacing non-printable characters in file names with question marks to ensure safe output.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------
16)ls -r:
description:
   -r, --reverse
              reverse order while sorting
output:
raakin@ubuntu-25:~$ ls -r
Videos     snap    Pictures  Music  Downloads  Desktop
Templates  Public  newc      linx   Documents
remarks:
The command ls -r in Linux lists files and directories in reverse order, reversing the default sorting order, such as showing items from Z to A instead of A to Z.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------
17)ls -s:
description:
   -S     sort by file size, largest first

output:
raakin@ubuntu-25:~$ ls -s
total 44
4 Desktop    4 Downloads  4 Music  4 Pictures  4 snap       4 Videos
4 Documents  4 linx       4 newc   4 Public    4 Templates
remark:
The command ls -s in Linux displays the size of each file in blocks alongside the file names when listing directory contents.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------
18)ls -t:
description:
  -t     sort by time, newest first; see --time
output:
raakin@ubuntu-25:~$ ls -t
linx  Downloads  Pictures   Music   Videos     Desktop
newc  snap       Documents  Public  Templates
remark:
The command ls -t in Linux sorts and lists files and directories by modification time, showing the newest files first.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------
19)ls -u:
description:
   -U     do not sort; list entries in directory order
output:
raakin@ubuntu-25:~$ ls -u
Desktop    snap  Videos    newc   Documents  Public
Templates  linx  Pictures  Music  Downloads
remark:
The command ls -u in Linux lists files and directories, sorting and displaying them by the last access time instead of the modification time.

-------------------------------------------------------------------------
20)ls -v:
description:
-v     natural sort of (version) numbers within text
output:
raakin@ubuntu-25:~$ ls -v
Desktop    Downloads  Pictures  Templates  linx  snap
Documents  Music      Public    Videos     newc
remark:
The command ls -v in Linux sorts and lists files in a natural version sort order, meaning it sorts numbers within filenames in a way that humans expect (e.g., file1, file2, file10) rather than simple ASCII sorting.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------
21)ls -x:
description:
  -x     list entries by lines instead of by columns
output:
raakin@ubuntu-25:~$ ls -x
Desktop    Documents  Downloads  linx  Music  newc  Pictures  Public  snap
Templates  Videos
remark:
The command ls -x in Linux lists files and directories in a horizontal, comma-separated format across the terminal screen, filling each line before moving to the next one.

